,Recommended,304730,30954684,Posted: 4 April,all,Krupo,"I conditionally recommend this game. Things to keep in mind when I say ""conditionally"":- I'll share my silliest gripe first: I'm pretty sure the trailer should say this is ""digital heroin"" not ""heroine,"" but it doesn't look like the developer will ever re-create their trailers, so that cute typo stays with us for the ages.- On the topic of things never changing, Transport Fever has stolen its thunder, but that's to be expected when quasi-sequels emerge - it has been almost three years since this title came out, after all. This does mean you're going to live with the game's quirks without much in teh way of changes, so you'd best be getting this on a good sale!- There are persnickety background rules. Fail to deliver within 20 minute? Your passengers spontaneously disappear. If you can't accept this, don't read any further, go find a freeware copy of the original Railroad Tycoon instead.- The interface is the gaming equivalent of working with SAP or any other program with minimalist UI. You have to adapt to its quirks rather than vice versa. The developers, to their credit, finally added a dialogue to let you see your old saved game names so you can over-write a prior save if you like doing that sort of thing. I originally used 1-letter saved game names because there was no way of clicking and selecting your old saved games. This, plus finicky track laying mechanics, are prime examples of the challenges you used to, and still deal with, respecitvely.This review started off as a comment to the discussion boards asking whether this game had any life left in it. I started with the following anecdote: I hadn't touched Train Fever in 11 months, but the introduction of Transport Fever inspired me to go back to this game and a world I had paused on. It's still great fun, but a source of occasional massive frustration. I built a small junction of tracks which confused the heck out of the pathfinding - of course this led to all passengers abandoning my profitable mainline route because it appeared to not exist even though the trains still knew where to go!Absolutely bizarre - I realized I had a problem when my $30M cash stockpile began crashing to less than half that (I was distracted by other side projects connecting spurs).In the end I destroyed the buggy junction, rebuilt that chunk of mainline and re-created the entire route. This interface issue actually brought a bit of a challenge back to the game, as I had inadvertently created my own ""rescue your company from your own sloppiness"" scenario.Compared to the original Tycoon games I miss a bit of the challenge from fighting real competitors on the map as opposed to the imaginary cargo transport forces and the tyranny of the automobile stealing your customers, but all-in-all, it's still an addictive timesink. And the graphics are average to gorgeous depending on how you admire the world, so that's a plus too. Did I mention the free DLC adding North American vehicles makes it especialy awesome, given the number of Canadian transit vehicles? That's a big plus too."
