76561197974920126,Recommended,304730,12031235,"Posted: 8 September, 2014",all,Sir Meowric,"After seeing all the negative reviews I thought I'd put in my two cents.  First, I think this game is awesome.  So naturally my review is biased, but so is everyone else's.  In order to follow the established trend here is my bullet point list of good and bad traits.Good:-modern graphics engine-realistic train physics:-speed is adjusted based on angle of curve, incline/decline, weight, and power to name a few of the ones I've noticed-tracks must follow the same rules as real world train tracks (eg.  no steep hills, no sharp turns, 90 degree road crossings)-train signals are realistic and easy to manage-play your way (eg. city management, train empire, trading mogul)-easy to use menu and interface-dragable windows with real time feedback on anything and everything-your actions affect the size of your cities in real time-procedually generated so always something new-did I mention how fun it is?Bad:-no manual / poor tutorial-repetative-steep learning curve (bad?)Here's where I defend my review and tell you why all the negative reviews are wrong.  First, the complaint I read the most is that there are too many rules regarding track building.  That is the ""simulation"" part of the game, trains have a very low tollerance for sharp curves, steep hills, and road crossings.  Get over it!  The other main complaing is the lack of manual, well here you go:Train Fever Interactive Gude:  (Link Removed...just search train fever website forums for great interacive guide)Your welcome!The most useful advice I learned is that the maximum travel time for people or goods is 20 mins, and the npc's will pick the quickest route regardless of cost."
