76561198103468164,Not Recommended,304730,28111905,"Posted: 30 November, 2016",all,Havan_IronOak,"I came to this game from a background of  RailRoad Tycoon 3  (Released 2003)  9.99 USD on SteamRailroad Tycoon 3  is getting a bit ""long in the tooth"" and I was hoping for an upgrade. While Railroad Tycoon 3 is not as pretty, in my judgement it is a superior game to Train Fever (and its sucessor Transport Fever) in many ways.Railroad Tycoon 3 has no signals and these are an improvement, it did have water towers and maintenance sheds that are absent from Transport Fever. Growing up in a railroad town spoiled me but I'd also expect a turntable.Railroad Tycoon 3  has no mechanic for returning empty freight cars for re-use. This game has them but unlike real world railcars, almost all wagon types are for a single commodity only. e.g. Why aren't coal hoppers and iron hoppers interchangeable?Railroad Tycoon 3  has a robust economic game with 30+ commodities in 1,2 and 3 deep production chains. Transport Fever has maybe a dozen commodities.Railroad Tycoon 3  had the ability to buy stock in your company and learn about the benefits (and dangers) of margin buying - no such thing exists in Train Fever.Railroad Tycoon 3  had a more robust undo ability for laying rail.Railroad Tycoon 3 had 66 Historical Locomotives rather than the 45 offered in Train Fever.Railroad Tycoon 3  had debt that changes as to rates making refinancing something that must be contemplatedRailroad Tycoon 3  had the ability to start (or buy existing) industries and businesses so as to further develop your transport empire.Railroad Tycoon 3 had AI Competitors that may require that you buy them out in certain scenarios.Railroad Tycoon 3 had AI Competitors based on real world people who played roles in the development of the Railroads. You got a bit of history with your gaming.Railroad Tycoon 3  had economic cycles that affect supply and demand. Nothing like it exists in Train Fever.Railroad Tycoon 3  had 20+ scenarios that really encourage you to explore the intticacies of the game . Train fever is pretty much sandbox only.Railroad Tycoon 3  had overview maps that made spotting industries and resources (and the demand for them) much clearer than anything offered in the ""fever"" games.Railroad Tycoon 3 had  the ability to build water towers and maintenance barns and the need to consider such things.Railroad Tycoon 3  had well laid out Train lists that show at-a-glance status information that you cannot see as easily in the ""TF"" gamesOh Yes... Transport fever offers planes and boats as well as rail and road transport. Unfortunately the basic UI and AI challenges that were handled so deftly in the antique Railroad Tycoon 3 are still handled somewhat poorly in Transport fever.There WAS and still is a lot of room for improvement in both games. Neither addresses switching engines. Those little workhorses that set up the long trains that we see crossing vast distances.  No marshalling yards are supported.  No telegraph service (an integral part of the US Railroads)  is modelled.Transport Fever LOOKS like a great game. I just wish that the devlopers paid more attention to what had gone before and incorporated some of the ""things that worked"" into their game design.I've played Train Fever quite a bit and once you get used to the demand driven economic model rather than the supply/price driven model used in the earlier game. It can be fun. But I do get a bad case of the ""mightabeens"" every time that I start to compare th game with its predecessor.Now the discount offered to Train Fever owners  for the improved Transport Fever"" brings the price down to $30 USD.The discount is going to have to be much deepr than that before I add  planes and boats and ignore the other shortcomings of the game.BTW... there ARE a few things that the developers could have done differntly that would have improved my rating:1) Track laying - Same day undo - allow any track laid to be demolished (on the same day) at no cost. This would somewhat make up for the lack of a real in-game track planning mode.2) Enable ESC as a means of bringing up the main loading menu. The current method wastes time and screen real estate.3) Make it easier to reload a saved game. I'm not sure whether this has been fixed in Transport fever but it required actually quitting and restarting the the game in Train Fever.4) Options should also be available via the escape menu. If one wishes to turn off the game sounds or something similar one has to quit Train Fever. Why was music the only one that can be silenced in-game?5) If you're going to do windows DO WINDOWS. Windows should be resizeable. Scrollable left and right as well as up and down. Cut and paste renaming should be enabled as well. Allowing for longer names would be good too. Default names suggested based on terminals would be great.6) Put a confirm on save game deletes. It was far too easy in Train Fever to delete the latest save game if one generally deletes a few saved games at start up time.7) As with any simulator with economic aspects, graphs would be nice. Or even improved statistics on trains. 5 and 10 year running averages of revenue expenses profits, passengers.The graphs on cities in Train fever were there and useful but could be greatly expanded on.8) How about a column on the industry list as to whether or not it's using a transport line. It's in the individual window so why not on the list?9) Signals are important in this game. They should be easier to see whether zoomed in or out.10) The Manage lines window should be sortable on Time, et al11) Station list should be sortable on cargo12) A button for next on line or next should be available in the vehicle details window13) The Mouse zoom feature should be more granular (more interim steps)14) A Trainopedia feature would be great.15) Towns list should show Goods needs supply and a few more details that are now only viewable in the city windows16) Commodities should be easier to see on a fully zoomed out map.17) If this game were look more like Railroad Tycoon III as to GUI features, it would be great."
,Recommended,304730,12322197,"Posted: 1 October, 2014",all,Wizard,"Don't get me wrong. Train Fever is not a perfect game. There are some performance issues on larger maps, some aspects of micromanaging are tedious, and I question the balance between train and truck income.That said, it's still a pretty decent game in a genre that doesn't get alot of love. And if you enjoy building train lines and roads and such, there's a good chance you'll find something to like in Train Fever.I really like the UI, which is really important in this kind of game. It's simple, unintrusive, and fully customizable. You can follow any number of vehicles, lines, charts, etc. I also like how when you have a window open, like of a vehicle, you can zoom within the window, click on a building within the window, and that will open a new window.The building and terraforming tools are quite good once you have them fully figured out. Graphics could be better, but they don't distract from the experience. Good music.Even with its flaws, I can still recommend this game. If you have any fond memories of the transport sims of yesteryear, Train Fever is worth a play."
76561198060801507,Recommended,304730,14041214,"Posted: 17 January, 2015",all,Bloodbunny,"Wonderful game! Its fine as vanilla, and even better with mods. It's like having your own living model railroad, without spending a fortune. As the game goes on, the towns grow toward your stations, buildings, cars, and even the pedestrian's clothing styles change. You can spend hours just getting your lines set perfectly; the learning curve is not too steep, yet the gameplay is pretty complex, with each individual citizen having their own schedule, home, and workplace.All that complexity has a bit of a price though; I don't recommend playing a map size larger than ""small"" if you have a 32 bit system. Even with 64 bits, the game will start to lag toward endgame (there are now mods to help with that though.)The graphics are a bit cartoonish, which I think was the point, its like a model railroad, not intended for hardcore realism. The sounds are fine, but the music soundtrack leaves a bit to be desired IMO, it doesn't fit the mood of the game at all.Overall, I HIGHLY recommend this game if you are interested in trains, model railroads, or transit systems at all."
