76561198039071218,Recommended,304730,13205286,"Posted: 2 December, 2014",all,GoatMutt,"It's definitely not polished YET, but it works. The developers even allow modding. Buy this game and give them the support necessary to really get this train rolling."
76561198153045246,Recommended,304730,13033993,"Posted: 21 November, 2014",all,Beamng.mapper.Bob.Blunderton,"IF YOU LOVE TRANSPORT TYCOON OR OPENTTD AS IT IS NOW CALLED, BUY NOW!For veterans of Transport Tycoon [deluxe]/ TTDPatch, and OPENTTD, this is a game you will have quite a time with, for quite a time!  For 20 years I've been holding out on one of the best Truck/Train shipping/logistics games, Transport Tycoon (also: now OPENTTD)... and now we have a 3d version.  Albeit it does not have all the fancy configurables that OPENTTD does, any fan should pick this up.The game engine is quite similar to CITIES XL, but without the glitches and other issues of XL, that is where any semblance to XL ends however.  This game is definately right in the same flavour of Transport Tycoon, so if you like that one, I can recommend giving this a try.  You might just become absorbed for the whole evening in it, unable to let go.  Quite challenging to make profitable train routes, though busses are pretty easy to work with in terms of turning a profit, one should start there.  A few bus lines up and running in a few different towns, then link them with trains.  Make sure your bus passengers get dropped off near the trainstations in each town, and you'll have a good train service in a few years time.  Remember, as in real life, people will want to use their cars more and more as an alternative to the logistics services you provide, especially as the years progress.  This coupled with the fact that every year equipment gets older, it costs more and more to maintain.  Keep this in mind if you're thinking about short-cutting your train route with a super-highway.  People will notice this and ridership will fall for your trains drasticly.  There is a mod to change the simulation's car max speed to encourage more folks to use your transportation, use that mod if you can't seem to turn a profit, but only as a last resort.  The challenge keeps this game fun through the years.  There isn't quite the hard falloff that TTD had, once you got to a certain point is was easy cruising without a care in the world.  Here, the challenge stays especially if you overlook things or become complacent.This game was quite rough when it first was released, but now with the patches, and the FREE USA DLC (via the DLC or STORE page for this game), there is so much more to offer, and a lot less bugs.This game can run for over 10 hours and not have crashing issues.Good patches last fall/winter and now the DLC update allowed me to update my review.  Train & Bus lines now working as intended, especially where they were problematic before when upgrading.  Loop routes work excellent, give them (and any train or bus line) a few years to mature fully + the grow with town growth, just like in Transport Tycoon.Landscaping/terraforming tools leave a bit to be desired, can take some time (this is no Simcity).  I can now build farther and longer than before with a section of rail without it failing to smooth terrain.  Before the patch it was mayhem trying to keep with the grade/slope.  You shouldn't have too many problems.  Building a road across double-railroad track is next to impossible, however, so you should lay roads before laying dual traintrack where and when possible.  It is possible to cross with bridges in most instances or tunnel under if you have the room, but this can be quite a test of patience at times and may prove a waste of time in certain respects.   On the flip side, since the patches the other month, building rail over road is much easier.  You shouldn't have too many instances where you cross roads in a manner that prevents you from laying track.  Try to build over the roads closer to a 90 degree angle to make things easier, even if it means making the track bend a bit.Remember, running a successful business may be challenging, but it is also rewarding.  Very Very rewarding, mind you.  Staying on top of things, with all the effort it takes, really comes with a good sense of accomplishment.  You might really enjoy this one, it's turned out to be a diamond in the rough after the updates - it really shines brightly!Would be nice to have bigger map size for those of us without lag issues, could build rail systems like they were meant to be.  I don't think the computer processing power/video processing power is quite there yet to be honest, for bigger maps.  Don't let this stop you.My only one complaint is being unable to lay road overtop double-raid track without knocking the track out first.  Sometimes also, the game may not let you remove certain roads if it feels the road is necessary to the simulation of people moving on their own.  You may have to fool around a bit building a bypass or two before it will let you remove the offending road if it's the only access between two towns or between a town and industry.  This is realistic, however, so who am I to judge negetively on this matter.Graphics are plenty good for a modern game, way better than 20 years-old gfx.The USA DLC is really stunning, and is free, so definately a feather-in-the-cap for the developer, especially considering there are many (purposely) community-source models here (the developers actually enlisted the help of modders to package this all up and purpose it for something totally awesome for everyone to enjoy).  Moves like this are extremely respectable, as they really give the customers value for their money spent buying the original game.Sound is on par where it should be and music is better than many other city-builders, though it is typically the jazz/muzak kind of thing.  Fairly typical of the simulation genre.  It doesn't seem to get as annoying or bothersome as the music from Simcity 4 however.  If you liked Transport Tycoon's music back in the day, you'll most likely be okay with this.Sound effects are appropriate and expected, they do not dissapoint.Really is becoming an awesome game.  I followed this game development via youtube for a few years, and I am glad to see it finally mature into a stable, enjoyable product that without a doubt sucks me in for many hours, sometimes a whole night.  I can't say that about too many games.Don't let the mention of Cities XL push you away, XL is not near as fun, addicitive, and bug free as this game is.  This game is 64bit, and multi-processor compiled.  This will use every bit of gfx and cpu horsepower you can throw at it.  i5 or i7 strongly recommended to play on the largest maps without any significant lag.  To turn on all the bells and whistles graphically, you'll want atleast a radeon 7700/7800 series graphics card (R 260 or better!).  This will run on intel integrated gfx but again a good Radeon or Geforce video card would be recommended for the largest maps on the higher graphical settings.Users with only 4gb of ram may wish to bump up their machines to 6gb to 8gb total system memory or more, as this game was using 3.5gb of ram on a large map, to help avoid hitching and lag that having only 4gb or less will give you.  Load times on a solid state drive are plenty fast so also no worries here.  If you use a small or medium map you may not need more than 4gb but see the system requirements for more detailed info.Plenty of community mods are available, but with the recent update this past week, you'll want to make sure you clean out all your old mods, and update them to the new versions otherwise you'll have a bad time with things.  The game gives you an option to load/unload mods right from the menu screen and there are front-ends for this purpose also that work with the DLC.  Check the Steam Forums for more info on this, as it is posted.Do enjoy, if you loved TTD, you'll enjoy this quite a bit!  To the developers personally, thanks for finally giving us a game to give us our OPENTTD/TTD fix, as after 20 years +, I think it's time for an update to the old favorite.  Still love TTD though, as always will.This game is 100% non-violent, and child friendly, but also deep enough for adults."
