76561197976088223,Recommended,304730,12043064,"Posted: 10 September, 2014",all,stubblychin,"I've played this for nearly 24 hours.  I wanted to give it a good play before reviewing.  Let's just say I've had a lot of fun with this, to a disturbingly addictive level.Stuff I like:+ Nice big maps.  Bright colours but it adds to the charm+ Cities Grow+ You can watch a single person go to work and back on your network.+ Once you pull off a complicated track arrangement it is incredibly satisfying.+ The way cargo works makes sense to me.  You can't just deliver coal to a factory and presume you'll make money.  The factory has to have it's goods going somewhere too.+ You find all kinds or nice looking views and moments when touring your network, a track wrapping around a hill, or a large train emptying dozens of people at a station where a bus is waiting.There is a somewhat steep learning curve at the beginning, mainly because there is barely any manual and only a brief tutorial.  There are plenty of steam guides though so make sure you read them before playing.  A little tip for those just starting: Build your railway lines in smaller chunks, and avoid going directly up a hill.There are a bunch of weird little bugs, for example, you can build tracks over roads but not roads over tracks, which you have to work around, but it seems the developer is still working on things, and there are bug fixes on the way apparently.If you are coming from Transport Tycoon to this, be aware it doesn't do everything the same, in particular, trains only use one assigned platform at a station (devs also working on this).If you are thinking of buying this, don't be fooled into thinking this is not an intensive game on your system.  Double check your system specs before buying.Also, this game is mod friendly and there are already fan made mods available, including a largely expanded cargo network."
