76561198116146209,Recommended,304730,14138291,"Posted: 23 January, 2015",all,SanditeSpartan117,"~~AS OF APRIL 1, 2016~~Train Fever offers some great gameplay and trasportation simulation that made me think, ""Just one more delivery"" then it's one hour later and the sun is about to come up. I was very hesitant at first when I was reading the reviews, then I watched a playthrough on YouTube and the urge to buy it was eating me up on every video I clicked, so I finally musterd up and bought it. I certainly don't regret it and the reviews that people are nagging about are relatable, but definitely tolerable. Of course it has it's flaws, and yes, it is lacking on other key features... Such as a world editor or even scenarios. This game has none! All you do is just build routes for trains, trucks, trams, and buses. Don't get me wrong, it is a fun game. The level of simulation and detail is very stunning when you get down to street level. The way the game tracks every citizen in every city, then those citizens have their own destinations such as, work, leisure, shopping, and home. You can either follow your tains, or follow someone's life. This is what really gives me a rich gaming experience is just how detailed it is.Although this game offers much playtime, after a while, you run into some obsatcles... After you unlock every vehicle, you run into a ""what now"" situation.. especially if you already connected every town and industry. You do have achievements to unlock, but those aren't exactly 'scenarios' per say. I really wish this game had some kind of opposing AI or scenario/campaign option and a world editor as well so you can make your own scenarios.Some people call it a ""tycoon"" game, but it's honestly not. You don't ""own"" a company, and you don't ""own"" any industries. You literally just build lines for your vehicles and make/lose money. There is an economic model in the game, but it's basic. It's not like the Railroad Tycoon series kind of economy where it was rather advanced.One of the most annoying things that take away from the experience is when you need to upgrade your bus stations/train stations. When your cities grow, more people will use your lines and time advances so you get really nice and new stations, but you first have to destroy the old ones. Oh, and if you have buildings really close, you'll have to destroy those too before you build your new one!, which can be very costly! The game gets real finicky when you try to make/change: bridges, stations, crossings, and tunnels so beware! The game engine is not fully optimized since it's custom made for this game. So, be aware of that after many in-game years your cities will become large. And as they grow, your game will start to suffer in FPS. It doesn't matter how beefy your PC is, it will struggle to keep your FPS above 30 if you have a city with 1,000 people.The devs need to implement an upgrade system for your stations where you click once and hit 'upgrade' instead of making it harder to bulldoze and stuff, but that was just me from playing Railroad Tycoon 3.The PROSthe simulationthe amount of detailgraphics are good, although some others would disagree, but it's not about the realism in this caselots of vehicles (trains, buses, trucks, trams...)towns grow into large cities which makes for an interesting gaming experienceFREE DLC (USA DLC)mod support, and built-in modsmoddable config files which goes to my previous bulletThe CONSlaying track/roads can be tedious at timesupgrading roads/stations can be difficultno tutorials, scenarios, or opposing AIyou can lay track over road, but not road over trackgame optimization isn't the best for late game (low fps)My Rating: 8/10A good gaming experience if you're willing to put up with the finicky crap."
