76561197970999694,Recommended,304730,13609039,"Posted: 26 December, 2014",all,renfe,"A total surprise. I played for hours the first time I launched it. Really fantastic, fun train simulation -- with buses and trams to get goods around cities & to stations. Seems to be modeled after the original Railroad Tycoon (which is a good thing), it lets you build tracks and schedule trains, and actually has signalling, something which later RR Tycoon games ""optimized"" away. The early years have slow trains, and you have to patiently build up your company. Expand too fast and you'll go broke. The graphics are gorgeous, tons of detail, fast.Some aspects are a little rough, clearly parts of the UX were an afterthought, but these aren't critical to the game."
,Recommended,304730,17495338,"Posted: 11 August, 2015",all,Paikia,"I really liked Sid Meier's Railroads. When I discovered Train Fever and decided to buy it, I really hoped it would be a worthy successor, as Sid Meier's Railroads is pretty much an antique by today's standards. I've been editing this review quite a few times as I've been playing and learning the game, and after playing for around 25 hours, I believe I finally have a good enough perspective to give a thorough and fair review.The positive points:1) The game is, or at least *should be*, fun to play, if and when it works properly. Needless to say, I wouldn't have wasted 25 hours playing a game I didn't enjoy playing, so that fact speaks for itself.2) The vehicles look good, graphically. I can't judge for myself how accurate and realistic they look, but by reading other reviews and comments, I got the impression the developers did quite a good job about that.3) The soundtrack is nice and fun to listen to while playing.The negative points:1) The performance is *really* bad. I have a decent PC. Nothing too fancy or cutting-edge, but enough to run most modern games smoothly on medium-high settings (Cities: Skylines, for one). Train Fever, on the other hand, barely works. It starts out okay, but as soon as the cities get a little larger than their starting size and there are over 30-40 vehicles moving, the game stutters constantly. I read somewhere that the main reason for that is that the game only uses one CPU core, as it doesn't support multi-core. All in all, the game seems not to use the hardware resources it has, which implies poor programming.2) The interface is very uncomfortable, there are no tutorials or in-game beginner-friendly guides to help understand how the game works. The information screens are vague and confusing. You pretty much need to learn the basics by trial and error, which is quite frustrating, considering you also have to struggle with the lousy performance while at it. I work as an accountant and I deal with companies' financial reports on a daily basis, but even I have been having troubles figuring out the financial data the game gives me about my company. Totally counter-intuitive. Needless to say, I know practically nothing about engineering or anything related to trains, which seems like a serious disadvantage when playing such a game. I've managed to improve a bit in my track building skills, but I'm still pretty clueless about how the cargo industries work, and the little I do know - I had to learn from a guide I read online. The little information the game gives about that is so cryptic, that it made me wonder what the developers had in mind when they released the game in such a state.3) Not enough content. There are no AI competitors, no random events, no side-quests, missions or anything else to make the game more interesting. While the game could be interesting enough without all those things (if it worked properly), they would sure be an important addition.All in all, I only recommend this game to hard-core fans of the genre, and even then - I'd suggest waiting for it to go on sale. For anyone else, I'd suggest to pass on this game. Not worth it.===========EDIT (August 7, 2016):While I stand by my analysis of the game, I decided I've been enjoying the game so much (as evident by my play-time counter, that has already passed the 100 hours mark), that it would be unfair on my part to leave the negative rating as it is, so I'm about to flip it to positive."
,Recommended,304730,15048970,"Posted: 25 March, 2015",all,Cleaver,"Train fever feels like it hasn't reached its full potential yet, that said I still think it is worth a play. There are a few things I would like to see improved such as more diverse freight loads, more trains and vehicles and better track tools. As it stands I can't make a double crossover which means to make large station crossovers takes a huge amount of space to achieve. The patches have made a big difference and the new US DLC which is free has added more to the game. The game would also benefit from the Steam Workshop if it was intergrated as there are already a large amount of mods available for this game.There are other transport builders out there but I think Train Fever is still a good buy if its on sale. If you love transport games then you shouldn't look passed this title."
,Recommended,304730,13699738,"Posted: 29 December, 2014",all,SGTSylver,"I don't have any other train gaming/sim experience so my opinion is only off of this game and not how it compares to others. Also, I'll add some minor tips/spoilers at the bottom for new players.The game is fun and initially very challenging. The lack of tutorial information or quality ""let's play"" guides and videos left the learning/discovery pretty much to trial and error. But the process was fun and because it was challenging it caused me to want to do it more. One initial trial game on small/flat/easy allowed most of the advanced features to be figured out. And FYI to all new players the videos and forum posts on creating bus routes and cargo lines was all based on the AI prior to recent patches. My experience did not show those tutorials as being accurate and was a bigger source of frustration than anything in the game itself.The game is more difficult initially than most maybe, but as long as you like the city/world management types of games but on a transportation level you can spend some enjoyable hours on it.  The graphics are good and it is neat to follow your trains/vehicles around, especially across that bohemoth bridge you built just for the sake of doing it.Spoilers/Noob Tips:• Build rails in small steps to avoid heavy $$ costs.• Local bus routes are keys to developing a prosperous city, and may not be lucrative themselves.• Big picture perspective is needed to get you through the long game.• Not all resources are to be connected to a town or factory• Most resources should NOT be connected via rail, early on anyway.• Signals and waypoints are your friends, use them"
