,Recommended,304730,16047386,"Posted: 28 May, 2015",all,Matt Lowden,"I'm going to write this review in stages as I feel this game is a slow burner. I've played for just over 10 hours so I'm going to update this review over course of the next few weeks. Please note that I genuinely want to love this game and will probably spend at least 100 hours playing it. For the record I bought the game on sale for about £6.10 HoursSo far I've found the game confusing and fragmented. the tutorial is a little brief and fundamentally the game isn't very intuitive. I have played several games, often realizing my errors and starting again as a recursive learning process. The game focuses on road and rail transport; so far I've found that creating a rail link between two cities is very profitable but introducing a third city creates a lot of problems due to difficulties managing which trains manage which lines.I haven't been able to make a profit on inter-city bus lines as people simply won't use the bus service despite using conventional wisdom when plotting the bus route between the various city regions.Natural resources seem to move at random between starting games. Sometimes lots of natural resources are produced and can be moved between locations and you can make a mint, and sometimes absolutely nothing is produced meaning there is no reason to even bother with them.Train lines are confusing and creating more complex train routes is convoluted to the point of not being fun. Creating simple A-to-B routes is more profitable and is easier to manage.ConclusionSo far I've enjoyed the game, in principle, but still feel like there's a huge amount of room for improvement. The basics are there but a lot of time needs to be spent on balancing and tweaking how the game works."
