,Recommended,304730,15110268,"Posted: 29 March, 2015",all,Arfski,"If you like building things, watching trains move around a landscape like a virtual model railway then you will probably enjoy this game. Good graphics, gameplay, and ever changing cities keeps the game fresh and if you don't like the world you have created, then go get yourself another randomly created map.There are some aspects that can be tiresome, such as what has become for me the dreaded terrain collision when trying to build across existing items, and the 'must build bypass first' before deleting town connecting roads. There are some things that could be tweaked from an ease of use point of view, but they do not detract from the overall game.The game clearly benefits from being actively developed, and new features come along all the time, the recent free DLC that adds a USA style map for example.Edit: Recent updates, and a clearer understanding of the game mechanics has made the game even more enjoyable, the danger is that you lose yourself in it and lose track of time far too easily. At the current discounted price this is a must have for anyone that enjoys sims, if you are a ""Tycoon"" style game fan or otherwise."
76561198019607050,Recommended,304730,15611205,"Posted: 29 April, 2015",all,mj.kent,"Nice game with some limited touches. Having played Railroad Tycoon(RT), RT2 is my main playable (replayable) game of this type. RT3 and Railroads were poor implimentations of this type of operating/ management sim. Train Fever goes along way to redo this type of sim and the graphics are very good. Similiar feel to Cities in Motion(CiM) which I have over 1000 hours playing. The time is worth it and I would still play CiM if it had a slight improvement in CiM2 but it appears to have had a complete rewrite to the interface which has put me off.This game takes me back to RT2 but with the ability to build tunnels! It takes a little work getting how the interface works  but have now played 25 hours and am still learning some of the more advanced gameplay features. Do not be put off because the game is a joy graphics wise.What are my limited touches:Firstly, only 3 levels of difficulty (Easy, Medium and Hard) whereas in RT2 you could set your own level (if only a little) in the scenarios.Secondly, it looks like no scenarios are provided each new game builds a new map. I enjoyed playing the NE corridor and Mid west scenarios in RT2 so it's a bit of a shame that these maps do not appear available. (Note: I have not yet tried the USA(DLC) so this maybe corrected.)and Finally, Not enough choice of trains and resources. This limits the game somewhat but too many resources would make it Transport Tycoon a game I dislike a lot!After reading all this is the game worth it? Yes but do not expect quick action and that suits me a lot!One other issue for me is the use of mods. I am not very technical so why put additions in through mods? It would be better from my point of view to have mods as part of a DLC package which could then be chosen before a new game begins. Any thoughts are welcome!The ingame music is very good (Admiral James T - Cricket Post /Harvest)anybody know if it is to be released?"
