,Recommended,304730,16101294,"Posted: 31 May, 2015",all,GoodOlAndy [Win10],"Bought this game because everyone says it is like Sid Meiers Railroads, a game I love but can not play since switching to Linux.Now the only similar thing is the building of train networks between cities and resources but that is where it ends.  The game actually is more complex.  Laying of tracks and setting up trains requires more work than Railroads.In Railroads you simply lay your track then pick your train and train cars for that section of track.  In Train Fever you must do more, like create a train depot which MUST be connected to the track you want to train to be on.  I could not figure out how to delete a train nor have I figured out yet how to properly connect resources.  BTW, every station MUST be connected to a road which makes placing your tracks even harder.On top of creating train routes, you also need to create bus routes to move people around each city to your train station.Unlike Railroads though, there doesn't appear to be any computer players to compete against.  For some people like myself, this can result in a not as fun game but if you are a huge fan of sim city type games where there is no one to compete against then you should enjoy this game."
76561198009203044,Recommended,304730,16666932,"Posted: 23 June, 2015",all,Minmator,"Train fever is a good and fun game to play overall. It is in my opinion the best train tycoonish game around at the moment and judging from past updates, it should get better with time.Pros: It's fun! Nice graphics (maps, trains, other vehicules), good audio design, unique music, easy to use building tool.Cons: Building tool needs more advanced options for more complex networks, performance gets bellow average on large maps in the late game, yearly savegame process is horrid.TF features a sandbox setup and very good looking proceduraly generated maps. It is really just that though a sandbox and it doesnt feature any tycoon options like campaigns and/or competition. Instead here you are fighting the elements such as hills, rivers, main roads, vehicules decay, etc. The maps look good and not two games are the same since they are generated. If however you are looking for real world maps, you won't find it here.So what do you actually do when playing TF? You build train, tram, bus and otherwise truck lines to move either passengers and/or cargo around while trying to make enough money to survive another year.So how is the building tool since it's most of what we do in this game? It's okay but not great.Building basic rails/roads is easy enough once you learn how the tool reacts to roads and rivers for example. It always try to save you money by proposing the most economical option (bridge, tunnel?, going over?). It also tries to make the best curves and slopes possible automaticaly. Setting up two lines next to each other is also a charm since the tool acts like a magnet and nicely sticks that 2nd line next to the 1st one. For all the basic stuff, it's great.The building tool really lacks more robust features though, features such as seen in other titles like Cities Skylines. In short, you can't easily cross any other line that already exists. The tool isn't letting the player decide on elevation (page up/down in Cities: Skylines) and there's no way to build X or + connections between two lines. Sure there are tricks around this but it isn't friendly and it makes a mess. As long as you focus on building railroads for EITHER passengers OR cargo, it's fun enough. But as soon as you try to setup multiple lines for BOTH passengers AND cargo, the building tool just falls short. You see, passengers and cargo require different kinds of stations. But since there is no way for a line to go over or under an existing line, it's just not fun to try and build large rail networks for both passengers and cargo. You end up with a spaghetti of parallel lines preventing you from building additional ones.As a result cargo trains are being left out for the most part and focus is more on passengers ones. It feels like a whole portion of the game is not accessible because the construction tool isn't robust enough and that is my main issue with this one.Sure experiencing better performance on large maps, being able to buy industries, maybe have credit quotations for loans and see more tycoon features being added would be nice. But first, fix the building tool.I recommend this game because despite it's obvious flaws, it's fun in it's current state and there are indications it should get even better.Thumbs up!"
76561197978866994,Recommended,304730,15884360,"Posted: 18 May, 2015",all,Azrael,"Train Fever has some flaws and is not a perfect game and lacks some features, but it is the best in the genre, since the last games are either made for childs (looking at you Sid Meiers Railroads) or the last games that have the features, that TF lacks, are very old (RT-Series, Open TTD and others).The developers are still actively working on the game and supporting the modding community, if you look at other devs and other games, this is not a standard.So, if you're looking for a transportmanagementgame with appealing graphics (I'm not a graphic who.re myself but even I despise the 2,5D pixelated graphics of Open TTD), Train Fever is your best shot and you can't do something wrong with buying it.PS: I recommend to have atleast 4 GB RAM on your rig. I have 8 GB myself and I have no performance problems at all. So I guess 4 GB is acceptable and not bad, since they announced another performance patch."
,Recommended,304730,29419400,Posted: 22 January,all,Rebel_Guy,"First off, this game is a ♥♥♥♥ing piece of♥♥♥♥♥♥ don't buy it.Secondly, this game is an addicting masterpiece, go buy it.This game reminds me a lot of OpenTTD, but without confining the user to the grid system, and also in 3D. And also with really good graphics.There are some extremely annoying bugs and poor implementations of some features. Things that I can think of at the top of my head:- The way that vehicles are guided through intersections is a pain in the pineapple, and often unnecessarily causes delays of 20+ minutes. This is especially annoying early in the game, and/or on hard mode.- The terrain is extremely difficult to deform, given the limited and pretty much broken tools available.- Vehicles never change lanes/tracks, but instead their routes are absolutely hardcoded. This means that, for example, a train will not ""choose"" the best available platform at a station, but instead wait until its designated platform is free.- The amount of money analysis tools are very limited, and overall vehicle management is pretty much non-existent.As frustrating as it is, this game is beautiful, addicting, and super satisfying. If you like OpenTTD-style games, you should consider buying Train Fever."
