76561197982239451,Not Recommended,304730,16122126,"Posted: 1 June, 2015",all,kenthenson,"1. Frustrating. Non-existent tutorial makes this a tough game to jump into straight away. After spending an evening watching YouTube videos, I was finally able to get a business up and running and breaking even. Raw materials are scattered across the map, as expected, but the factories are also stuck out in the middle of nowhere, instead of congregating in the industrial sectors of your towns. Not having the ability to build new factories, where you really need them, is also extremely irritating.2. Fun. Not nearly as playable as Sid Meiers' Railroads and with no real goals or opponents it boils down to a straight builder. If you like SimCity or Banished, this is for you.3. UI. Horrible. To track performance and profitibility you need to have several windows open which cover most of the play area. With no ability to push these windows over to a second monitor you have to pause often to review your status. When new trains become available there is no accompanying information to let you know if they are passenger or freight trains.I really was expecting more. Hopefully there are expansions, updates or mods out there to make this a better, more satisfying gaming experience."
76561198203592720,Recommended,304730,17458717,"Posted: 9 August, 2015",all,The painter,"I have played many games of this genre before, including Locomotion, all of the Transport Tycoons, Railroads!, all of the Railroad Tycoon games and a few others, and never before have I encountered a product as well balanced and easy to use as this. Granted, the economy works differently than most other games in this genre. For example, in most transport games, trains only run when they are full of goods in order to make a profit, however, in Train Fever, running trains without them needing to be full is essential to make a profit, because, much like in real life, a train on a siding is burning fuel and going nowhere, while its load decays in value. The game is well priced and has a strong user interface that is easy to use and a refeshingly easy approach to replacing and re-routing vehicles. I higly recomend this game to anyone that wants to think while playing a game, and or is interested in logistics and transportation.Pros:1. Easy to use and understand interface2. Infinent possiblities for every diffferent map3. Amazing graphics and genrally good polish on everything4. Hyper-relistic simulation5. Fun and interesting mechanics make for a great expriance6. Runs smooth on max settings on my pc (AMD six core 3.5 Mhz, 16 Gb RAM, 3Gb graphics, 750 watt power supply)7. Makes for a lot of fun for a good price8. Devs are adding more every month or soCons:1. Lack of good tutorial, recomend going to the fourms and reading about mechanics of game before playing2. Not a huge diversity of vehicles, can be fixed with mods3. You won't be succesful on your first try, its a thinking game, and takes time to learn the ropes4. Small dev team means progress is slow5. No AI competitors6. Production cap on industries, just a personal pet peeve of mine. It should be about 1000, accounting for the economic value of one unit of goods carried to one city and the nubmer of jobs provided by that good, but its capped at 4006. Not many useful guides on steam, go to the fourms for better ideas and solutions"
