76561198230177148,Recommended,304730,33959845,Posted: 1 August,all,The Viking,"Personally, I prefer Train Fever to Transport Fever. Transport Fever is what Train Fever should have been all along, but it's too late to change that (or even complain about it).The game does come with its fair-share of issues, such as annoying collisions, random transport issues with some vehicles, no proper tutorial (even if, after 140 hours you should have mastered the game, it just takes a few tries to learn the basics) and some other issues that aren't really worth mentioning (the truth is, I can't remember them....).Gameplay is what you would expect from your usual transport-tycoon sim. You start in a certain period of time, set up passenger and goods lines, make money, refine the routes, make more money, and you keep going until you've covered the needs in goods & transport of each one of your cities.The randomly generated maps are also a nice touch, as it does make the replayability quite interesting.The game will also regularly go on sale for 1/4 of its price, so it's a really good value for what you're getting.All the achievements can be obtained, but some will require hours of work."
