,Recommended,304730,16773630,"Posted: 28 June, 2015",all,david_c,"Train Fever is an addictive little transport simulator. It has some clear limitations, but for a casual sim fan it was easy to lose many(!) hours watching the trains and busses go 'round.It follows the template of Railroad Tycoon or TTD, so you'll be moving people or 5 different goods between cities and factories via rail, tram, or bus/truck. As you improve transport around the map, towns will grow, creating ever-increasing volumes of traffic.There's no stock market, ticket prices, or AI competitors - you just need to provide better transport for each resource (people and goods are individually tracked and can walk/drive a fair distance on their own to fulfill their needs).Even the smallest map is quite large, so rail will be a big focus. The most fun is to be had in laying track and getting your switching (though essentially just 1 type of signal) set up. Then you watch you (increasing terribly expensive) trains do their dance. As time progresses different types of vehicles become available, and you will need to work to find the right balance of routes, transport types, and number of vehicles to make a profit.The art, landscape, and animations are nice but nothing exemplary, and while there seem to be a good number of vehicle models, at any given time there's not a lot of variety (especially early game, where you will probably spend your first 10 hours or so). Variety is probably the biggest problem, as new industries don't seem to appear, there are no dynamic events/disasters/crashes, the routing logic is very basic, and there are no advanced track features (e.g. multi-switch sections).That said, there are some smart, modern touches to the interface that you will really appreciate (except no undo...) like being able to sort to visible routes, auto-healing routes, combining stops, and easily visualizing individual lines. If the developers continue to expand the content, this could become great game. As it is, I can still wholly recommend it to anyone looking for some light transport strategy."
