76561198131585871,Not Recommended,304730,20054689,"Posted: 28 December, 2015",all,Eugen Bold,"TL;DR: Buy on sale, and only on saleWhen I first bought this game and played ~3 hours, I was enthralled. This game had reignited a passion for trains (steam trains especially) that I hadn't had since I was 10. The game immersed me in a potent mixture of nostalgia and wonder. I recommended the game based on these feelings.Another ~5 hours later and the illusion of wonder has worn off. The cracks have begun to show, and now I understand why reviews are mixed. Because the game is essentially a mixed bag - here's why.My specs I've been playing this on are:Intel Core i5 @2.5GHz8GB RAMIntel HD 4000 Graphics (mobile)I'm gaming on my subpar school laptop. The game actually doesn't look bad on the lowest settings. Stutters a bit when zoomed completely out and viewing the full map, but as long as I don't zoom out completely, it plays pretty well. Props to the game for that.Moving on: the gameplay - you build bus routes to ferry your passengers around inside cities, build train stations in these cities to connect cities to each other, and watch as the passengers line up at the station, begging to be allowed onto one of your fancy railroad cars. Add sidings, loops, or even another whole length of track to allow more trains to ferry your passengers between towns. Expand to another town, repeat the process! Dig tunnels and build bridges! (you even get to choose your kind of bridge truss!) Add more cars to your trains and upgrade them as technology advances with time! Cargo trains are much trickier (based on what gameplay I have they seem more like a late-game feature), though they are much more complex than simply connecting passenger lines together. Hook up different industries and resources like coal mines, ore mines, sawmills, and more and connect them to goods manufacturers like oil refineries, lumber yards, and more! Pay off your initial starting loan and make millions! Sounds great, right? Well, it is. What ruins the experience in the long-run is the UI.The first (and biggest) mistake the game makes is lumping all your bus and RR lines for all cities into ONE management window. Doesn't seem like a big deal, right? Not at first. But it becomes really frustrating later on when I'm trying to see which bus lines correspond to which railroad lines, which ones are running cargo, and why some bus lines are losing money. Every line is numbered. So if I create two bus lines in three different cities, and then connected two of the cities with one RR line, it would look like (ignoring the parenthesis and the words inside parenthesis):LINE 1 (bus line city 1)LINE 2 (bus line city 2)LINE 3 (bus line city 3)LINE 4 (railroad line for city 1-city 2)Yes, each line is color-coded, but that doesn't significantly alleviate the problem. Additionally, the way line numbers are listed, it's extremely wonky. Say I have 30 bus and railroad lines. The game will list the lines as follows:LINE 1LINE 11LINE 12LINE 13[...]LINE 19LINE 2LINE 20LINE 21[...]LINE 29LINE 3LINE 30THIS IS HOWTRAIN FEVERNUMBERS ITS LINES!!!It becomes a logisticalnightmareto manage your trains. Make no mistake, large corporations can be bureaucratic minefields to one degree or another, butTrain Fevertakes it to an unreasonable level.The other major part of my beef with this game is the laying of track. Specifically, train stations. So I want to have a passenger station and, the way I was planning it, I was going to have a cargo train directly across from the passenger station. No biggie, right?WRONG, WRONG WRONG!!!> try to build cargo station directly across from passenger station with tracks in between> TF hates me> lay down second line of track and over a road just outside of where planned stations will be> creates two-line railroad crossing> still can't build cargo station without the game raging on me> give up after 45 minutes> try to delete one of the lines crossing the road> TF wants me to delete both> rage> begrudgingly delete double-RR crossing> try to lay down new track to reconnect original passenger station>Unable to place track> Rage> delete road> able to lay track> try to repave road>Unable to pave over track, you must build track after paving road> RAGEOn that note, the game will seemingly at random not want to place track in a given spot or create a split line for whatever reason. It's frustrating when it seems it happens for no good reason.I bought this over winter sale for 80% off ($6 USD). That's all it's worth."
