76561198030874808,Not Recommended,304730,22208222,"Posted: 2 April, 2016",all,Hoh Ceh Geh,"A swiss company tried to do the next ""Transport Tycoon"", but they are not Chris Sawyer  (the creator of the Transport Tycoon games) and now we are not in the 90's.The result? They built a slow-at-the-end tiny-map game that at maximum is a communter train simulator for a middle-sized city in a incredibly boring map. Graphics, other than trains, are simply ""meh"". Plus, you do by far more revenue with buses (in a game called ""TRAIN fever"") that with trains, even more, you go bankrupcy with trains if they are no 100% full all the time and only 5 years old.What has gone wrong? Easy, Chris Sawyer developed the original game using a programming language called ""Assembler"" that allowed him to juice ALL the resources of the computer at that time so the result was amaizing. The swiss team but used a 3D engine base, that also is based in tons of another programs, so they had little control of where the resources of the computer are spent. Actually is not their fault, the 3D simulation and its level of freedom of possibilities is by far more complex than the 2D graphics of the original game plus using that kind of programs is a normal choice by small software companies.What to do? Play OpenTTD (it's FREE), and if you love it, help it to fund a better graphics patch. That's all.Finally, please note that is simply impossible to do a decent high-scale 3D transport game, too many resources spent for a game that will be used by not a big chunk of people (hoping that I'm wrong about that last sentence)."
