,Not Recommended,304730,13824354,"Posted: 3 January, 2015",all,Hendo,"I'm afraid that I cannot recommend this game after several hours of playing it.There are some positives, and one massive negative (which I'll get to in a minute):+ The line layout is simple and intuitive, it actually does work pretty well... by and large. There are a couple of oddities here and there (particularly if you've got stations on both sides of a road, for instance) but these are easily resolved.+ The individual track laying mechanism is a great idea. However, it does come with quite a few caveats.+ Gameplay is pretty straightforward, you gotta get things from point A to point B, but be prepared as you may lose money at first.And now... the big negative:The amount of time that I have spent getting frustrated with trying to build rail bridges over roads is getting ridiculous. I've pretty much given up on the game because the editor is a pain in the butt to work with.Thought process as follows goes:""Ooh, this looks like a good place to cross over the road. It's perfectly straight and there's plenty of room to do it!""But then...NOPE. Can't do it. Nope, nope, nope, the terrain editor will find it absolutely UNACCEPTABLE and you can't build it. Never mind that the approaches look fine, everything looks fine, and argh, I just give up.Want to build a nice, compact rail overpass that *doesn't* require pillars? Nope, not gonna happen, may as well forget about it.For now, I can't recommend the game, but this will probably change IF the developer is interested in actually fixing the many issues with the game."
76561198062413497,Not Recommended,304730,14367698,"Posted: 7 February, 2015",all,ValleyC4t,"For a game called ""Train Fever"", the execution of the namesake is just not very good. Simple cargo-truck, bus, and even tram lines are plenty workable. However, when you start trying to build railways, you run into lots of intractable problems:1. The handling of elevation in rail tracks/stations is not good. Stations seem to be elevated off the surface of the map (and the terrain raised), or recessed into the ground, for no obvious reason. It's hard to build tracks between relatively near stations, because the system wants to build them at a high slope.2. Trains often have trouble finding their way on really straightforward rail routes, even when you're using things like waypoints. Conflicts between trains are far too common, and the use of signals is complex and fraught with peril. Basically, forget about having more than one train per track, and expect persistent headaches at terminus stations.3. It's possible to end up in a state, especially on multi-train lines, where your trains are PERMANENTLY stuck and you simply must revert. That's unacceptable.4. Train Fever doesn't let you do anything with elevation, except in the form of the afterthought hacks in the path-finding phase during build. No elevated or subway trains, making it hard to do much better than streetcar/tram light rail in the cities.5. The cities grow so slowly that they never really arrive at the sort of scale that makes a transit system a fun challenge. On easy, you build a few cargo lines, cash in and watch the money stream in. On the harder difficulties, it's a challenge to make headway at all."
