76561198044544643,Not Recommended,304730,11980616,"Posted: 4 September, 2014",all,Impatient,"----------------------------------------2014-09-11 update after 58 hours----------------------------------------I stopped playing this game. Where by ""playing"" I mostly mean figuring out how it works, WHAT in it works and to find workarounds for things that are supposed to work but do not. This is because no game mechnics are explained anywhere. (Frequently reading and participating in the forums, where players exchange knowledge, is the best bet to figure out this game.) And also this is because the game is full of bugs and design flaws. Still. I would be not mad at all, if this game was Early Access. But it is released and financed via crowdfunding.I stoppped playing this game because to me it is more frustrating than fun. Maybe this will change. I am visiting the train-fever website weekly, to see if there is a new patch (and release notes). And I hope I will read, that the bugs that upset me so much, got fixed, one day.But until then I do not recommend to buy this game. I recommend to hold your money and wait, until the game matured.----------------------------------------2014-09-07 after 20 hours of game time----------------------------------------i would like to have my money back. seriously. i would wait half a year and observe if all the bugs and design flaws get fixed and the game gets an overhaul so it is more challenging and fun and less painful and frustrating.i loved transport tycoon back in the early years and today i still play railroad tycoon 3. but train fever at this stage is simply not fun to play. train fever looks nice, in some ways, yes, but there is very little versatility in this game. just 5 cargo types? small maps? very few vehicles? no ai competition? no option to build industries? no financial market options? expensive trains in a train game? the landscape looks the same everywhere? no sandbox mode? (i am not even asking about multiplayer)i miss the fun of competing the ai opponents, ruining them and finally taking over their companies. i miss the fun of managing 30 different cargo types, i miss the fun of watching a lot of different locomotives with different train cars for each cargo type ploughing through the landscape.btw, in train fever you wont have a lot of trains. road vehicles are the main source of income. just on routes with a very high concentration of cargo or passengers, trains are profitable. road transportation is really very dominant. suggesting to rename this game to ""road fever"" or ""transport fever"" would not just be a joke.the usability is medium at best. managing a large transport network can be painful. i wont bother you with how hard some advanced goals can be to achieve. but a simple example: you can not build a rail crossing when you want to cross a road over a track. this feature simply is not implemented. you just can cross tracks over a road. meaning, to cross a road over a track, you need to bulldoze the track, lay the road, and then cross the track over it. ...and then there are the bugs. ... disappearing cargo, blocked truck stations, stuck trains, wrong cargo count. ...also the game lags even fast computers, the user interface is ugly and uncomfortable, the music is horrible and better turned off, sound effects are poor. though the graphics are detailed, the landscape looks boring greenish and repetitive.and the gameplay as a whole ...  no goals, no challenges, no missions, no opponents. the only goal is to build the perfect transportation network, grow cities and industries, to increase the need for transportation. ... well to be honest, in this last regard, the game is not very different from other games in this genre.it is the multitude of frustrating things. that make me not like to play this game for now. it needs a huge amount of work to get out of a development-/testing stage."
