76561198006990645,Not Recommended,304730,12061897,"Posted: 11 September, 2014",all,hawkeye,"After 140 hours of gameplay, not recommended.  It is a very boring game.Do not believe the minimum specs listed - not even close to accurate.Graphics are poor - dull, drab and lacking crispness.Railway operations are too simplistic and do not work like a real railway operations. (when I saw steam engines running at speed pumping out black smoke I should have realised then that that the devs probably did not know much about trains)Many bugs still to be fixed.Signals are invisible except on max zoom level.Track laying is a pain even when it decides to behave correctly.The industry/goods side of things is very weak.Game maps tend to be repetitive.  Played one map then you've played them all.And the showstopper - there are too few trains.  One train will usually be enough to service an entire line connecting 5 or 6 towns.  In the 20 or so games I have played the most trains I have had running is 5.  The game becomes one where you watch 1 or 2 trains run back and forward over a featureless landscape, then upgrade them when a new engine becomes available, and then sit there and watch the 2 trains run back and forward over a featureless landscape, ........  It's like a record playing the same song again and again.There is no incentive to build long lines as exist in the real world because no-one wants to go anywhere far away.  There is a 20 minute rule where the population won't travel at all if the entire trip is longer than 20 minutes (which equates to the next train stop usually).  This is possibly a result of modelling passengers individually.  Each boid chews up cpu and so the game has been dumbed down to minimise the number of boids but maximise the number of boid trips by making maximum trip length quite short.  End result is that the game just doesn't feel like a real railway."
