76561198101788565,Not Recommended,304730,15347854,"Posted: 13 April, 2015",all,purchases,"I have several different train simulators and games at this point and this is pretty much the worst of them. The in-game help is horrible, disconnected, and basically doesn't get you up and ""running"". As others have noted, it's trying to jam too much into one game so it feels very half-butted rather than doing one or two things whole-butted. The panning and scrolling are jerky and feel very ""shareware"" like. The graphics are pretty rudimentary. For example, when creating a tunnel you get an angled mess that looks like a bottomless quick sand pit rather than a nice entrance and exit to the tunnel. Even the main menu looks like a major accident when you change to higher resolutions. Errors are even funnier! You'll get errors like ""Not enough space"" when you're trying to connect a road to a station...in the middle of a pasture! Or ""Collision! Terrain alignment collision. Not enough space"" What the heck does THAT mean?When you're building a track, to scroll the landscape you have to continue holding down the left mouse button to lay track while at the same time holding down the right mouse button and moving the mouse in the opposite direction to scroll the screen. Really? Did anyone teach these developers how to write software? When laying track it automatically curves when you want to go straight...and then you get another error messages that have more meaning in a C++ compiler than in a train simulation game. It seems like the designers got into a room and decided on the following tenets:1. Make the help as useless as possible.2. Make the error messages even more useless than the help.3. Make the controls for the UI as useless as the error messages.4. Make the graphics look as close as possible to Pac Man.5. Make the game extremely unintuitive to chase potential customers away so that we can go bankrupt.6. Charge a lot of money so we came make as much as possible before declaring baankruptcy.This wasn't worth the money it cost me, and I would HIGHLY STRESS that if you're thinking about buying this game, invest in a tree stump instead...it'll provide less aggrevation and more entertainment that this game."
