76561198060593979,Recommended,304730,26112807,"Posted: 19 October, 2016",all,miranda9,"Graphics are tops and as eye candy it succeeds.City grow and building change from year to year.The rivers are well done and look wet.Cars and people change appearance as game years pass.As a railroad simulator is is limited to track planning with several unanticipated reasons why you cant build where you want.   Cities grow and may block future track plans. Industries are a challenge to predict future product levels.  Freight trains are  harder to manage and require a good guess as to the level of future traffic revenue .  Making route adjustments late in the game can result in rapid decline in revenue.  Game control is made awkward  by the use of  multiple windows for tasks that block scenery and rapidly fill the screen with text. Single window information and control would be an asset to game enjoyment.    Changing the consist of a line will  void all  built up development of traffic on that line,  so plan for this when adding stations or reemoving stations.  Growing a railroad is best done by adding a new line rather than extending existing lines.This program was run on a gaming computer (Aspire V 17 Nitro. Ttrying to resume the game after a save and exit often  displays a  greyed out selections on start up screen which prevents further play. Small and medium screens are least likely to cause lag and crash problem on this Aapire laptop.|In spite of game mechanics and lag problems experienced, there is sufficient enjoyment to overcome frustrations and give this game a yes."
,Recommended,304730,35079163,Posted: 20 September,all,GLaDOS,"Although the game has some issues (and was abandoned after the release of Transport Fever), I have some great fun with this game."
76561198083517758,Not Recommended,304730,35485104,Posted: 4 October,all,LeadKronos,"I bought this game as a fan of Chris Sawyer's Locomotion (literally the same thing) and figured this was a polished  spiritual successor of the game, so I was  hyped when I bought it. I was expecting everything I had gotten from Locomotion. It was like drinking Coke Zero for the first time: expecting the same great thing but with added benefits, but instead got a huge letdown. The game runs like in playing on an Asian TF2 server in the middle of nowhere. The game also lacks a dedicated tutorial session, which is something that definitely should be in a game like this and yet it instead relys on outside sources for help. So im spending the first two hours trying to figure out how things work and by then, you cant really get a refund after the two hour mark. The buses and trucks are ok, but God forbid you get into building a rail network. The construction mechanics, will always give you a ridiculously hard time while jacking up prices like how certain tech companies charge you an arm and a leg for phones. It costs 3 million to build a train tunnel through a mountain and then you end up in the red for atleast 5 years. The line mechanic seems unecessary especially when the train has only two stops. Then the train would rack up about 50k in running costs before making its first profit every two months. So far in my first 10 hours if this game Im like: 'HTF am I gonna make money?!' After three playthrough attempts, im still  struggling. There is alot this game could improve on, hopefully, the dev will take note and either make a similar game with better mechanics or update this game to simplify the resource catchment and make it like Locomotion's. So far, it's worth the $3. Anymore and I would have rose h3ll."
